However, a more thorough root-cause fix would be to use `std::vector::begin()` or `std::vector::front()` instead of capturing an iterator before the loop. This ensures that the iterator remains valid even after reallocations:


```cpp
int main() {
  std::vector<int> vec;
  for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    vec.push_back(i);
  }
  int& ref = vec.back();
  // use ref
}
```


GLOBAL FIX:
Use iterators and references instead of capturing indices, especially in loops that may reallocate the underlying storage. This ensures that iterators and references remain valid and prevents use-after-free errors. Additionally, prefer `std::vector::begin()` and `std::vector::front()` over manual index calculations for guaranteed valid iterators.
